sub_title: Team Leader and Application Engineer at ASML
summary: I lead a team of engineers in the productivity and defectivity group of CS ABS in part of my time. Our team looks at data from ASML's customers to suggest customised productivity improvements based on their usage of lithography machines. I am involved in new product introduction and multiple stages of the product generation process. I also do data analysis and reporting as part of application and business support.

projects: [{'title': 'Project for TU Delft Science Centre: Source Localization and imaging using Surface Waves', 'date': {'start': {'month': 2, 'day': None, 'year': 2015}, 'end': {'month': 2, 'day': None, 'year': 2015}}, 'description': 'We use omni-directional surface wave recordings at areas around the Science Centre in Delft, in an attempt to determine the location of the source generating the surface waves. The aim is to obtain a ‘live’ source localization algorithm, showing the location / movement of for example a person walking in the field. As a final step, the surface-wave recordings can be used for imaging purposes, when a correct velocity model is determined. The results will be used as input for future Science Centre developments.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Ranjani', 'last_name': 'Shamasundar', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Team Leader and Application Engineer at ASML'}]}, {'title': 'Experimental engineering project', 'date': {'start': {'month': 1, 'day': None, 'year': 2012}, 'end': {'month': 1, 'day': None, 'year': 2012}}, 'description': 'Computational Fracture Mechanics and Displacement Field Measurement using Digital Image Correlation for the crack tip of a compact tension specimen.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Ranjani', 'last_name': 'Shamasundar', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Team Leader and Application Engineer at ASML'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Syam', 'last_name': 'P Venugopalan', 'name': None, 'headline': ' Researcher cum Intrapreneur: Enabling future semiconductor technologies'}]}, {'title': 'A non-local plasticity theory for amorphous metals and its implementation', 'date': {'start': {'month': 7, 'day': None, 'year': 2011}, 'end': {'month': 7, 'day': None, 'year': 2011}}, 'description': 'Recently, experiments and atomistic simulations have shown that metallic glasses display hardening behavior akin to metals. However, the underlying physical mechanism governing this behavior remains to be explained. In order to explain this, inspiration is drawn from earlier work on crystalline metals. As the sample volume reduces, the deformation behavior becomes sensitive to the imposed boundary conditions on the microstructural variables in crystalline materials. (Bittencourt,2003). In this work, an attempt has been made to study the corresponding effect in metallic glasses, by imposing microscopically free and microscopically hard boundary conditions. The simple shear simulations conducted show that small volume metallic glass samples display hardening when a sink-like micro hard condition is imposed. The result of “smaller is stronger”, which has been widely accepted in literature, has also been shown in this work. The plane strain tension and compression simulations show that as the length scale is increased (which equivalent is to reducing sample size), the deformation behavior approaches homogeneous conditions, and the ductility is increased to a large extent. Further, tension tests are conducted on notched specimens to study notch sensitivity effect in metallic glasses. It is seen that although there is an apparent reduction in the yield strength of the metallic glass with increasing notch size, the normalized ultimate tensile strength (strength of the unnotched specimen over the strength of ligament) remains insensitive to the presence of the notch. Also, it is seen that the plastic zone nucleates at the notch tip, and upon reaching a critical size, leads to the branching of a shear band. This effort is the first of its kind, where a continuum theory has reproduced the results of earlier atomistic simulations on notched metallic glass samples.
